      "id":"environment/blog/2013/oct/17/false-widow-spider-attacks",
      "sectionId":"environment",
      "sectionName":"Environment",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T11:08:47Z",
      "webTitle":"False widow spiders aren't out to get us – and their bite isn't dangerous",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2013/oct/17/false-widow-spider-attacks",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/environment/blog/2013/oct/17/false-widow-spider-attacks",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Mark Riley Cardwell: </strong>Don't panic, shelob lives in the middle earth and isn't likely to come out of Tolkien books</p>",
        "headline":"False widow spiders aren't out to get us – and their bite isn't dangerous",
        "body":"<p>The past few weeks have seen media reports claiming millions of <a href=\"http://news.sky.com/story/1153770/false-widow-spider-gives-boy-red-raw-wound\" title=\"\">\"flesh-eating\"</a> false widow spiders are rampaging across the UK - culminating in the front page of today's Daily Star screaming <a href=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/BWujkiICcAAqult.jpg:large\" title=\"\">\"Killer  spiders  attacked my little girl.\"</a></p><p>The alarming coverage might suggest the country is facing some kind of eight-legged apocalypse – but the  species poses nothing like the grave threat painted in the media, according to experts.</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2453833/Decorator-nearly-loses-leg-bite-UKs-poisonous-spider.html\" title=\"\">Daily Mail</a> and <a href=\"http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/343983/False-widow-spider-ATE-my-leg\" title=\"\">Daily Star</a> reported that a man nearly lost his leg after being bitten, with \"10 million\" of the critters on the march across the nation; a<a href=\"http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/344612/Mum-s-terror-as-FIFTY-venomous-False-Widow-spiders-race-towards-her\" title=\"\"> woman was chased by 50 of the \"highly venomous arachnids\"</a>; and regional papers from <a href=\"http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/VIDEO-Warning-killer-spider-false-widow-lurking/story-19916673-detail/story.html#axzz2hoDuMEew\" title=\"\">south Wales</a> to <a href=\"http://www.nottinghampost.com/False-widow-spiders-way-Nottingham/story-19930784-detail/story.html\" title=\"\">Nottingham</a> have suggested their area could be hit next.</p><p>But experts have called for a reality check, saying the false widows' bite is not seriously dangerous, and noting there are no recorded deaths from bites since the spiders first arrived in the country in 1879.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420248470'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/columnists/2013/10/17/1382004419231/Daily-Star-front-page-fea-001.jpg' alt='Daily Star front page featuring a False Widow Spider (Steatoda nobilis) attack' width='220' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>According to <a href=\"http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/about-science/staff-directory/life-sciences/j-tweddle/index.html\" title=\"\">Dr John Tweddle</a>, Head of the <a href=\"http://www.nhm.ac.uk/index.html\" title=\"\">Natural History Museum's</a> Angela Marmont Centre, populations originally lived in the south west, but have now become quite common across the south and south east.</p><blockquote><p>\"Yes, the species is both becoming more common and more widespread. It's not an influx as such, rather that existing populations are expanding. It is likely that this spread is at least partly a response to a changing climate and as such we're expecting the species to continue to increase its distribution within the UK.\"</p></blockquote><p>The reason we are seeing so many stories appearing now may simply be because spiders are moving indoors with the onset of colder weather following a particularly dry summer. Tweddle says:</p><blockquote><p>\"We tend to spot spiders most frequently during the Autumn as this is when many of the UK's larger species reach maximum size, so are most visible. The males of some species – such as Tegenaria house spiders – are also actively moving around in the search for mates, so more likely to be spotted.\"</p></blockquote><p>So how deadly are these animals? According to Tweddle, the noble false widow spiders (<a href=\"http://www.nhm.ac.uk/nature-online/species-of-the-day/biodiversity/alien-species/steatoda-nobilis/\" title=\"\"><em>Steatoda nobilis</em></a>) are not the rampant terror they have been made out to be.</p><p>The spiders are one of only around a dozen species capable of biting humans among the UK's 650 spider species, but bites are extremely rare – and are much less common than bee or wasp stings. He says:</p><blockquote><p>\"There have been very few confirmed incidences of bites from <em>Steatoda nobilis</em>, although adult female false widow spiders are certainly capable of biting humans if handled without due care – the smaller males are not known to cause bites. It is not an aggressive species towards humans and is most likely to bite when accidentally prodded or squashed, or trapped in clothing.\"</p></blockquote><p>The false widow is much less dangerous than the black widow spider – whose venom is said to be 15 times stronger than a rattlesnake. However, even black widow bites are unlikely to cause serious damage or death.</p><p>Despite the admittedly small risk posed by the eight-legged creatures, the media frenzy around false widow spiders is causing people across the UK to panic, <a href=\"http://srs.britishspiders.org.uk/portal.php/p/False+Widow+Spiders\" title=\"\">according to the British Arachnological Society</a>. <a href=\"http://www.lawrencebee.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Lawrence Bee</a>, the group's education and publicity officer, says:</p><blockquote><p>\"The media's reaction has definitely been over the top. We are quite a small society, and over the last few weeks we have been inundated with emails and phone calls from members of the public who have been really quite concerned about these reports. The problem is that they are seeing any spider as being a false widow spider.<br />\"We want to put some perspective on it. The false widow spider can bite, and if you are sensitive you can have a reaction to it – but no one has been killed by one in the UK. Some reports suggest we are in great danger.\"</p></blockquote><p>Bee even disputed that some of the scare stories were down to spiders at all. He says:</p><blockquote><p>\"The stories don't provide us with a clear picture. People think that because they have seen a spider just before they were bitten, it was the spider that bit them. One person said they had been bitten by a spider that had run across their foot. But why would a spider stop and bite someone if all it was doing was running across their foot? These things are not aggressive.\"</p></blockquote><p>In other words, we should all calm down – the spiders aren't coming to get us.</p><p>In fact, the experts' advice on what to do if you actually come across one is reassuringly straightforward. Tweddle says:</p><blockquote><p>\"If you are not keen on sharing your home with spiders, then it is best to catch and then release them away from your home. Try to avoid touching the spider – as well as the small risk of bite, spiders are easily damaged. A cup and piece of card is a simple way to catch, then transport the spider out of your home.\"</p></blockquote><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420242279|2013-10-17T15:37:00Z|ad33737ea94c24f7c030d48e026e1af06a4f1e0b -->",
